146
Tavata, Rast Africa,
18th June 1898
Dear Sir Clement Hill,
Encouraged by your kindness to me before I came out here
in January, I am venturing to send you a rough mar I have made
of the track here front Voi, a distance of 80 miles. I don't
think anybody las done one before and the track might easily
be shortened by about 15 miles if a proper road were made. This
I hone in time to be allowed to do. My only instruments were a
prismatic compass and an aneroid but I think the distances have
come out fairly correctthough the two maps I Have difter between
themselves as much as 20 miles in a mundred. The track varies
from 86 to 18" wide and twists round a very bush and stone until
Lanioro is reached and then there is a proper road about 20
yards wide from there to the German boundary.
I am loving it
cleared as my predecessor had let it get almost entirely over-
Crown The first two days waren Irom Voi to Bura was through
lovely country,well wooded and plenty of water. At Eura there
is a French Mission and they have larre sugar and banana
plantations. They also find that coffee and vines grow very well
and their garden was full of all kinds of European vetetables.
The track passes over a col 3200' high and then descens
steeply into the valley where the usual camp is. By making a
well to the south of the spur where there must be water as the
stream goes underground, the route could be very much shortened
and the steer climb avoided. The Serengati plain is uninterest-
ing except as regards same. Hartebeeste, Grantii le abounded and
I was able to keep the caravan in venison. I saw three hards of
Giraffe and tried to stalk one but they were too wily for me
and I had not time to follow them l'ar. There were also quanti-
ties of Ostrich. Sarengati is supposed to be waterless but I
can
